00:02.275 --> 00:07.220
Interview with Dr. Laura Summers, visiting 
fellow at Sri Lanka University, Bangkok,

00:02.275 --> 00:07.220
Thailand. Question one. Do you feel that the Khmer 
Rouge should be involved in a coalition

00:09.322 --> 00:13.066
government? Why?

00:18.512 --> 00:28.362
Let me begin to answer this question by saying 
something about how I understand the position of

00:18.512 --> 00:28.362
those who oppose having the Khmer Rouge in a 
coalition government. I think most of the...

00:32.262 --> 00:38.863
campaign against Khmer Rouge involvement in the 
coalition. is motivated by or informed by some

00:40.160 --> 00:50.193
Western notions of justice or morality. I have 
friends, and I'm sure you have friends, who say

00:51.075 --> 01:07.737
things like, they're responsible for so much 
killing, they don't deserve to be in power, or it

00:51.075 --> 01:07.737
would be immoral for them to be put back in power 
because it was for example unthinkable or immoral

01:07.717 --> 01:21.270
that the fascists in Germany should be put back 
into power after they were defeated in the war well

01:21.740 --> 01:47.275
i want to stress that

01:21.740 --> 01:47.275
the arguments that you hear about this tend to 
issue out of western experience and western

01:21.740 --> 01:47.275
values and they represent a projection of certain 
democratic ideas of representation

01:47.660 --> 02:02.407
And while I don't reject those values, and of 
course we support those values, I want to suggest

01:47.660 --> 02:02.407
to you that these arguments are unrealistic. 
They're unrealistic if you look at the problem of a

02:03.429 --> 02:11.423
coalition government within the framework of 
Cambodian politics. so now let me answer the

02:12.517 --> 02:41.798
question that's the introduction but my answer to 
the question is that of course the Khmer Rouge must

02:12.517 --> 02:41.798
be involved in the coalition government and I say 
this for two reasons I say of course they must be

02:12.517 --> 02:41.798
involved because of certain political and that 
includes military realities on the ground And the

02:42.233 --> 02:55.889
second reason I say they must be involved is, and I 
want to be very careful about how I say this, they

02:42.233 --> 02:55.889
must be involved because in some sense I would 
argue they deserve to be involved. And I say they

02:57.291 --> 03:07.583
deserve to be involved from the standpoint of what 
has been happening inside Cambodian

02:57.291 --> 03:07.583
nationalism. and when you look at Khmer Rouge from 
that standpoint you can see that they still have

03:07.563 --> 03:24.492
some support not as much as they had in the early 70s 
and maybe more than they deserve in quotation

03:07.563 --> 03:24.492
marks But the simple historical fact of the matter 
is that they are recognized by some Cambodians as

03:24.472 --> 03:51.019
the leading nationalist force, as a group of 
people who still by and large represent the

03:24.472 --> 03:51.019
interests of poor country people, poor peasants, 
and as people who in standing up against the

03:51.573 --> 04:14.458
Vietnamese invasion have in some sense 
vindicated themselves although I think nobody

03:51.573 --> 04:14.458
has forgotten about the suffering and the 
killings from the 1970s that would be pretty

03:51.573 --> 04:14.458
impossible because the scale was large OK, but let 
me sum up by saying They really must be involved in

04:14.962 --> 04:23.218
the coalition because that's the price, in some 
sense, for peace. Le Premier Rouge still have the

04:25.643 --> 04:36.143
largest, most disciplined, most coherent army 
and political movement whatever we think of it and

04:36.123 --> 04:52.225
certainly it's not a movement or party that many 
foreigners would join whatever we think of it they

04:36.123 --> 04:52.225
have political power on the ground And as you know 
in political science, we're talking about

04:52.525 --> 05:03.179
conflict resolution, we're talking about 
settlement of disputes. This is a process which

05:04.281 --> 05:12.171
involves compromise amongst those groups which 
have power of one sort or another. either military

05:12.151 --> 05:41.500
power as in the case of Khmer Rouge royal and 
culturalist power in the case of Sihanouk whose

05:12.151 --> 05:41.500
army isn't so impressive but Sihanouk himself is 
widely recognized as being essential to a

05:12.151 --> 05:41.500
coalition because monarchy is central to the 
sense of stability and well-being in Cambodian

05:12.151 --> 05:41.500
society so Sihanouk has a form of power which we can 
label social and cultural power, as well as

05:41.480 --> 05:48.927
political power. Monarchy is the fulcrum and has 
always been the center of Khmer politics. It's

05:54.873 --> 06:00.298
probably less the center of Khmer politics now 
than it was 20 or 30 years ago. But again, it's still

06:00.318 --> 06:03.161
important. Sihanouk represents a kind of power 
which must be taken into account in a settlement.

06:09.509 --> 06:14.257
